yred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Tailbois de Windsor was born about 1193, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William de Tallebois. She had at least 1 son with William de Windsor IV. She died about 1230, at the age of 39."},"et":{"Abt. 1193–Abt. 1230":"umbes 1193–umbes 1230","1193–1230":"1193–1230","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1230–1279":"1230–1279","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","Abt. 1193":"umbes 1193","1248":"1248","1279":"1279","1189":"1189","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","Abt. 1230":"umbes 1230","1193":"1193","Bradenlove, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Bradenlove, England, United":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1193–Abt. 1230":"noin 1193–noin 1230","1193–1230":"1193–1230","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1230–1279":"1230–1279","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","Abt. 1193":"noin 1193","1248":"1248","1279":"1279","1189":"1189","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","Abt. 1230":"noin 1230","1193":"1193","Bradenlove, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Bradenlove, England, United":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1193–Abt. 1230":"environ 1193–environ 1230","1193–1230":"1193–1230","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1230–1279":"1230–1279","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","Abt. 1193":"environ 1193","1248":"1248","1279":"1279","1189":"1189","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","Abt. 1230":"environ 1230","1193":"1193","Bradenlove, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","Bradenlove, England, Unite